      ],
      "content": "Welcome to <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Azure Premium Storage Disks<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> for faster Azure virtual machines."
    },
    {
      "content": "With the introduction of Premium Storage, Microsoft Azure now offers two types of durable storage: <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Premium Storage<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Standard Storage<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        699,
        843
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Premium Storage stores data on the latest technology Solid State Drives (SSDs) whereas Standard Storage stores data on Hard Disk Drives (HDDs).",
      "pos": [
        844,
        987
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Premium Storage delivers high-performance, low-latency disk support for I/O intensive workloads running on Azure Virtual Machines.",
      "pos": [
        989,
        1119
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can attach several Premium Storage disks to a virtual machine (VM).",
      "pos": [
        1120,
        1191
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "With Premium Storage, your applications can have up to 64 TB of storage per VM and achieve 80,000 IOPS (input/output operations per second) per VM and 2000 MB per second disk throughput per VM with extremely low latencies for read operations.",
      "pos": [
        1192,
        1434
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1436,
        1561
      ],
      "content": "To get started with Azure Premium Storage, visit <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Get started for free<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/pricing/free-trial/)</ept> page."
    },
    {
      "content": "This article provides an in-depth overview of Azure Premium Storage.",
      "pos": [
        1563,
        1631
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Important Things to Know About Premium Storage",
      "pos": [
        1636,
        1682
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following is a list of important things to consider before or when using Premium Storage:",
      "pos": [
        1684,
        1777
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To use Premium Storage, you need to have a Premium Storage account.",
      "pos": [
        1781,
        1848
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To learn how to create a Premium Storage account, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Creating and using Premium Storage Account for Disks<ept id=\"p1\">](#create-and-use-a-premium-storage-account-for-a-virtual-machine-data-disk)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        1849,
        2033
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        2037,
        2492
      ],
      "content": "Premium Storage is currently available in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft Azure Preview Portal<ept id=\"p1\">](https://portal.azure.com/)</ept> and accessible via the following SDK libraries: <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Storage REST API<ept id=\"p2\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com//library/azure/dd179355.aspx)</ept> version 2014-02-14 or later; <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>Service Management REST API<ept id=\"p3\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/ee460799.aspx)</ept> version 2014-10-01 or later; and <bpt id=\"p4\">[</bpt>Azure PowerShell<ept id=\"p4\">](../install-configure-powershell.md)</ept> version 0.8.10 or later."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        2496,
        2635
      ],
      "content": "For a list of regions that currently support Premium Storage, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Services by Region<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/regions/#services)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Premium Storage supports only Azure page blobs, which are used to hold persistent disks for Azure Virtual Machines (VMs).",
      "pos": [
        2639,
        2760
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For information on Azure page blobs, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Understanding Block Blobs and Page Blobs<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/ee691964.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        2761,
        2900
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Premium Storage does not support the Azure Block Blobs, Azure Files, Azure Tables, or Azure Queues.",
      "pos": [
        2901,
        3000
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A Premium Storage account is locally redundant (LRS) and keeps three copies of the data within a single region.",
      "pos": [
        3004,
        3115
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For considerations regarding geo replication when using Premium Storage, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Snapshots and Copy Blob when using Premium Storage<ept id=\"p1\">](#snapshots-and-copy-blob-when-using-premium-storage)</ept> section in this article.",
      "pos": [
        3117,
        3328
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you want to use a Premium Storage account for your VM disks, you need to use the DS-series or GS-series of VMs.",
      "pos": [
        3332,
        3446
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use both Standard and Premium storage disks with DS-series or GS-series of VMs.",
      "pos": [
        3447,
        3534
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But you cannot use Premium Storage disks with non-DS-series or non-GS-series of VMs.",
      "pos": [
        3535,
        3619
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For information on available Azure VM disk types and sizes, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Virtual Machine and Cloud Service Sizes for Azure<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn197896.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        3620,
        3791
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The process for setting up Premium Storage disks for a VM is similar to Standard Storage disks.",
      "pos": [
        3795,
        3890
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You need to choose the most appropriate Premium Storage option for your Azure disks and VM.",
      "pos": [
        3891,
        3982
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The VM size should be suitable for your workload based on the performance characteristics of the Premium offerings.",
      "pos": [
        3983,
        4098
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Scalability and Performance Targets when using Premium Storage<ept id=\"p1\">](#scalability-and-performance-targets-when-using-premium-storage)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4099,
        4255
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A premium storage account cannot be mapped to a custom domain name.",
      "pos": [
        4259,
        4326
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Storage analytics is not currently supported for Premium Storage.",
      "pos": [
        4330,
        4395
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To analyze the performance metrics of VMs using disks on Premium Storage accounts, use the operating system based tools, such as <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows Performance Monitor<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc749249.aspx)</ept> for Windows VMs and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>IOSTAT<ept id=\"p2\">](http://linux.die.net/man/1/iostat)</ept> for Linux VMs.",
      "pos": [
        4396,
        4686
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also enable the Azure VM Diagnostics on Azure Preview Portal.",
      "pos": [
        4687,
        4756
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Refer to <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft Azure Virtual Machine Monitoring with Azure Diagnostics Extension<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/blog/2014/09/02/windows-azure-virtual-machine-monitoring-with-wad-extension/)</ept> for details.",
      "pos": [
        4757,
        4961
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using Premium Storage for Disks",
      "pos": [
        4966,
        4997
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use Premium Storage for Disks in one of two ways:",
      "pos": [
        4998,
        5055
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create a new premium storage account first and then use it when creating the VM.",
      "pos": [
        5059,
        5139
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create a new DS-series or GS-series VM.",
      "pos": [
        5142,
        5181
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While creating the VM, you can select a previously created Premium Storage account, create a new one, or let the Azure Portal to create a default premium account.",
      "pos": [
        5182,
        5344
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure uses the storage account as a container for your operating system (OS) and data disks.",
      "pos": [
        5346,
        5438
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In other words, if you create an Azure DS-series or GS-series VM and select an Azure Premium Storage account, your operating system and data disks are stored in that storage account.",
      "pos": [
        5439,
        5621
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To leverage the benefits of Premium Storage, create a Premium Storage account using an account type of <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Premium_LRS<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> first.",
      "pos": [
        5623,
        5746
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To do this, you can use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft Azure Preview Portal<ept id=\"p1\">](https://portal.azure.com/)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Azure PowerShell<ept id=\"p2\">](../install-configure-powershell.md)</ept>, or the <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>Service Management REST API<ept id=\"p3\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/ee460799.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5747,
        5984
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For step-by-step instructions, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Creating and using Premium Storage Account for Disks<ept id=\"p1\">](#create-and-use-a-premium-storage-account-for-a-virtual-machine-data-disk)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5985,
        6150
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Important notes:",
      "pos": [
        6156,
        6172
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For details about the capacity and bandwidth limits for Premium Storage accounts, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Scalability and Performance Targets when using Premium Storage<ept id=\"p1\">](#scalability-and-performance-targets-when-using-premium-storage)</ept> section.",
      "pos": [
        6176,
        6404
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the needs of your application exceed the scalability targets of a single storage account, build your application to use multiple storage accounts, and partition your data across those storage accounts.",
      "pos": [
        6405,
        6609
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if you want to attach 51 terabytes (TB) disks across a number of VMs, spread them across two storage accounts since 35 TB is the limit for a single Premium storage account.",
      "pos": [
        6610,
        6795
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Make sure that a single Premium Storage account has never more than 35 TB of provisioned disks.",
      "pos": [
        6796,
        6891
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, disk caching policy is \"Read-Only\" for all the Premium data disks, and \"Read-Write\" for the Premium operating system disk attached to the VM.",
      "pos": [
        6894,
        7047
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This configuration setting is recommended to achieve the optimal performance for your application’s I/Os.",
      "pos": [
        7048,
        7153
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For write-heavy or write-only data disks (such as SQL Server log files), disable disk caching so that you can achieve better application performance.",
      "pos": [
        7154,
        7303
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Make sure that there is sufficient bandwidth available on your VM to drive the disk traffic.",
      "pos": [
        7306,
        7398
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, a STANDARD_DS1 VM has 32 MB per second dedicated bandwidth available for Premium Storage disk traffic.",
      "pos": [
        7399,
        7514
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "That means, a P10 Premium Storage disk attached to this VM can only go up to 32 MB per second but not up to 100 MB per second that the P10 disk can provide.",
      "pos": [
        7515,
        7671
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Similarly, a STANDARD_DS13 VM can go up to 256 MB per second across all disks.",
      "pos": [
        7672,
        7750
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Currently, the largest VM on DS-series is STANDARD_DS14 and it can provide up to 512 MB per second across all disks.",
      "pos": [
        7751,
        7867
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The largest VM on GS-series is STANDARD_GS5 and it can give up to 2000 MB per second across all disks.",
      "pos": [
        7868,
        7970
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that these limits are for disk traffic alone, not including cache-hits and network traffic.",
      "pos": [
        7976,
        8072
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is a separate bandwidth available for VM network traffic, which is different from the dedicated bandwidth for Premium Storage disks.",
      "pos": [
        8073,
        8211
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For the most up-to-date information on maximum IOPS and throughput (bandwidth) for DS-series and GS-series VMs, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Virtual Machine and Cloud Service Sizes for Azure<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn197896.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8222,
        8445
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To learn about the Premium storage disks and their IOPs and throughput limits, see the table in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Scalability and Performance Targets when using Premium Storage<ept id=\"p1\">](#scalability-and-performance-targets-when-using-premium-storage)</ept> section in this article.",
      "pos": [
        8446,
        8700
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Cache-hits are not limited by the allocated IOPS/Throughput of the disk.",
      "pos": [
        8704,
        8789
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "That is, when you use a data disk with ReadOnly cache setting on a DS-series VM or GS-series VM, Reads that are served from the cache are not subject to Premium Storage disk limits.",
      "pos": [
        8790,
        8971
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Hence you could get very high throughput from a disk if the workload is predominantly Reads.",
      "pos": [
        8972,
        9064
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that, cache is subject to separate IOPS / Throughput limits at VM level based on the VM size.",
      "pos": [
        9065,
        9163
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DS-series VMs have roughly 4000 IOPS and 33 MB/sec per core for cache and local SSD IOs.",
      "pos": [
        9164,
        9252
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use both Premium and Standard storage disks in the same DS-series VM or GS-series VM.",
      "pos": [
        9256,
        9349
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "With Premium Storage, you can provision a DS-series VM and attach several persistent data disks to a VM.",
      "pos": [
        9352,
        9456
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If needed, you can stripe across the disks to increase the capacity and performance of the volume.",
      "pos": [
        9457,
        9555
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you stripe Premium Storage data disks using <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Storage Spaces<ept id=\"p1\">](http://technet.microsoft.com/library/hh831739.aspx)</ept>, you should configure it with one column for each disk that is used.",
      "pos": [
        9556,
        9740
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Otherwise, overall performance of the striped volume may be lower than expected due to uneven distribution of traffic across the disks.",
      "pos": [
        9741,
        9876
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, the Server Manager user interface (UI) allows you to setup columns up to 8 disks.",
      "pos": [
        9877,
        9970
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But if you have more than 8 disks, you need to use PowerShell to create the volume and also specify the number of columns manually.",
      "pos": [
        9971,
        10102
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Otherwise, the Server Manager UI continues to use 8 columns even though you have more disks.",
      "pos": [
        10103,
        10195
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if you have 32 disks in a single stripe set, you should specify 32 columns.",
      "pos": [
        10196,
        10284
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use the <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>NumberOfColumns<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> parameter of the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>New-VirtualDisk<ept id=\"p2\">](http://technet.microsoft.com/library/hh848643.aspx)</ept> PowerShell cmdlet to specify the number of columns used by the virtual disk.",
      "pos": [
        10285,
        10482
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Storage Spaces Overview<ept id=\"p1\">](http://technet.microsoft.com/library/jj822938.aspx)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Storage Spaces Frequently Asked Questions<ept id=\"p2\">](http://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/11382.storage-spaces-frequently-asked-questions-faq.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        10483,
        10752
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Avoid adding DS-series VMs to an existing cloud service that includes non-DS-series VMs.",
      "pos": [
        10755,
        10843
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A possible workaround is to migrate your existing VHDs to a new cloud service running only DS-series VMs.",
      "pos": [
        10844,
        10949
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you want to retain the same virtual IP address (VIP) for the new cloud service that hosts your DS-series VMs, use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Reserved IP Addresses<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-networks-configure-vnet-to-vnet-connection.md)</ept> feature.",
      "pos": [
        10951,
        11159
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "GS-series VMs can be added to an existing cloud service running only G-series VMs.",
      "pos": [
        11160,
        11242
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The DS-series of Azure virtual machines can be configured to use an operating system (OS) disk hosted either on a Standard Storage account or on a Premium Storage account.",
      "pos": [
        11245,
        11416
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you use the OS disk only for booting, you may consider using a Standard Storage based OS disk.",
      "pos": [
        11417,
        11514
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This provides cost benefits and similar performance results similar to the Premium Storage after booting up.",
      "pos": [
        11515,
        11623
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you perform any additional tasks on the OS disk other than booting, use Premium Storage as it provides better performance results.",
      "pos": [
        11624,
        11757
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if your application reads/writes from/to the OS disk, using Premium Storage based OS disk provides better performance for your VM.",
      "pos": [
        11758,
        11901
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Command-Line Interface (Azure CLI)<ept id=\"p1\">](../xplat-cli.md)</ept> with Premium Storage.",
      "pos": [
        11904,
        11997
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To change the cache policy on one of your disks using Azure CLI, run the following command:",
      "pos": [
        11998,
        12089
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that the caching policy options can be ReadOnly, None, or ReadWrite.",
      "pos": [
        12159,
        12232
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more options, see the help by running the following command:",
      "pos": [
        12233,
        12297
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Scalability and Performance Targets when using Premium Storage",
      "pos": [
        12338,
        12400
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you provision a disk against a Premium Storage account, how much input/output operations per second (IOPS) and throughput (bandwidth) it can get depends on the size of the disk.",
      "pos": [
        12402,
        12584
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Currently, there are three types of Premium Storage disks: P10, P20, and P30.",
      "pos": [
        12585,
        12662
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each one has specific limits for IOPS and throughput as specified in the following table:",
