    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Make sure that there is sufficient bandwidth available on your VM to drive the disk traffic as explained in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Using Premium Storage for Disks<ept id=\"p1\">](#using-premium-storage-for-disks)</ept> section earlier in this article.",
      "pos": [
        13428,
        13653
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Otherwise, your disk throughput and IOPS will be constrained to lower values based on the VM limits rather than the disk limits mentioned in the previous table.",
      "pos": [
        13654,
        13814
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure maps the disk size (rounded up) to the nearest Premium Storage Disk option as specified in the table.",
      "pos": [
        13818,
        13925
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, a disk of size 100 GiB is classified as a P10 option and can perform up to 500 IO units per second, and with up to 100 MB per second throughput.",
      "pos": [
        13926,
        14083
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Similarly, a disk of size 400 GiB is classified as a P20 option, and can perform up to 2300 IO units per second and up to 150 MB per second throughput.",
      "pos": [
        14084,
        14235
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The input/output (I/O) unit size is 256 KB.",
      "pos": [
        14237,
        14280
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the data being transferred is less than 256 KB, it is considered a single I/O unit.",
      "pos": [
        14281,
        14367
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The larger I/O sizes are counted as multiple I/Os of size 256 KB.",
      "pos": [
        14368,
        14433
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, 1100 KB I/O is counted as five I/O units.",
      "pos": [
        14434,
        14488
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The throughput limit includes writes to the disk as well as reads from that disk that are not served from the cache.",
      "pos": [
        14490,
        14606
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, the sum of non-cache reads and writes should be smaller or equal to 100 MB per second for a P10 disk.",
      "pos": [
        14607,
        14721
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Similarly, a single P10 disk can have either 100 MB per second of non-cache reads or 100 MB per second of writes, or 60 MB per second of reads with 40 MB per second of writes as an example.",
      "pos": [
        14723,
        14912
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you create your disks in Azure, select the most appropriate Premium Storage disk offering based on the needs of your application in terms of capacity, performance, scalability, and peak loads.",
      "pos": [
        14914,
        15111
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> You can easily increase the size of existing disks.",
      "pos": [
        15115,
        15179
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if you wish to increase the size of a 30 GB disk to 128GB or to 1 TB.",
      "pos": [
        15180,
        15262
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Or, if you wish to convert your P20 disk to a P30 disk because you need more capacity or more IOPS and throughput.",
      "pos": [
        15263,
        15377
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can expand the disk using “Update-AzureDisk” PowerShell commandlet with “-ResizedSizeInGB” property.",
      "pos": [
        15378,
        15482
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For performing this action, disk needs to be detached from the VM or the VM needs to be stopped.",
      "pos": [
        15483,
        15579
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following table describes the scalability targets for Premium storage accounts:",
      "pos": [
        15583,
        15666
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Total Account Capacity",
      "pos": [
        15783,
        15805
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Total Bandwidth for a Locally Redundant Storage Account",
      "pos": [
        15836,
        15891
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Disk capacity: 35 TB",
      "pos": [
        15957,
        15977
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Snapshot capacity: 10 TB",
      "pos": [
        16005,
        16029
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Up to 50 gigabits per second for Inbound + Outbound",
      "pos": [
        16063,
        16114
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Inbound refers to all data (requests) being sent to a storage account.",
      "pos": [
        16147,
        16217
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Outbound refers to all data (responses) being received from a storage account.",
      "pos": [
        16220,
        16298
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        16300,
        16433
      ],
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Storage Scalability and Performance Targets<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn249410.aspx)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Throttling when using Premium Storage",
      "pos": [
        16438,
        16475
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You may see throttling if your application’s IOPS or throughput exceed the allocated limits for a Premium Storage disk or if your total disk traffic across all disks on the VM exceeds the disk bandwidth limit available for the VM.",
      "pos": [
        16476,
        16706
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To avoid throttling, we recommend that you limit the number of pending I/O requests for disk based on the scalability and performance targets for the disk you have provisioned and based on the disk bandwidth available to the VM.",
      "pos": [
        16707,
        16935
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your application can achieve the lowest latency when it is designed to avoid throttling.",
      "pos": [
        16939,
        17027
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the other hand, if the number of pending I/O requests for the disk is too small, your application cannot take advantage of the maximum IOPS and throughput levels that are available to the disk.",
      "pos": [
        17028,
        17224
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following examples demonstrate how to calculate the throttling levels:",
      "pos": [
        17226,
        17300
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example 1:",
      "pos": [
        17306,
        17316
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your application has done 495 I/Os of 16 KB disk size (, which is equal to 495 I/O Units) in one second on a P10 disk.",
      "pos": [
        17317,
        17435
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you try a 2 MB I/O in the same second, the total of I/O units is equal to 495 + 8.",
      "pos": [
        17436,
        17521
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is because 2 MB I/O results in 2048 KB / 256 KB = 8 I/O Units when the I/O unit size is 256 KB.",
      "pos": [
        17522,
        17622
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since the sum of 495 + 8 exceeds the 500 IOPS limit for the disk, throttling occurs.",
      "pos": [
        17623,
        17707
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note:",
      "pos": [
        17713,
        17718
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "All calculations are based on the I/O unit size of 256 KB.",
      "pos": [
        17719,
        17777
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example 2:",
      "pos": [
        17783,
        17793
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your application has done 400 I/Os of 256 KB disk size on a P10 disk.",
      "pos": [
        17794,
        17863
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The total bandwidth consumed is (400 * 256) / 1024 = 100 MB/sec.",
      "pos": [
        17864,
        17928
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that 100 MB per second is the throughput limit of a P10 disk.",
      "pos": [
        17929,
        17995
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If your application tries to perform more I/O in that second, it gets throttled because it exceeds the allocated limit.",
      "pos": [
        17996,
        18115
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example 3:",
      "pos": [
        18121,
        18131
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You have a DS4 VM with two P30 disks attached.",
      "pos": [
        18132,
        18178
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each P30 disk is capable of 200 MB per second throughput.",
      "pos": [
        18179,
        18236
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, a DS4 VM has a total disk bandwidth capacity of 256 MB per second.",
      "pos": [
        18237,
        18312
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Therefore, you cannot drive the attached disks to the maximum throughput on this DS4 VM at the same time.",
      "pos": [
        18313,
        18418
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To resolve this, you can sustain traffic of 200 MB per second on one disk and 56 MB per second on the other disk.",
      "pos": [
        18419,
        18532
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the sum of your disk traffic goes over 256 MB per second, the disk traffic gets throttled.",
      "pos": [
        18533,
        18626
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note:",
      "pos": [
        18632,
        18637
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the disk traffic mostly consists of small I/O sizes, it is highly likely that your application will hit the IOPS limit before the throughput limit.",
      "pos": [
        18638,
        18788
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the other hand, if the disk traffic mostly consists of large I/O sizes, it is highly likely that your application will hit the throughput limit instead of the IOPS limit.",
      "pos": [
        18789,
        18962
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can maximize your application’s IOPS and throughput capacity by using optimal I/O sizes and also by limiting the number of pending I/O requests for disk.",
      "pos": [
        18963,
        19120
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Snapshots and Copy Blob when using Premium Storage",
      "pos": [
        19125,
        19175
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can create a snapshot for Premium Storage in the same way as you create a snapshot when using Standard Storage.",
      "pos": [
        19176,
        19291
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since Premium Storage is locally redundant, we recommend that you create snapshots and then copy those snapshots to a geo-redundant standard storage account.",
      "pos": [
        19292,
        19449
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Storage Redundancy Options<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn727290.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        19450,
        19566
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If a disk is attached to a VM, certain API operations are not permitted on the page blob backing the disk.",
      "pos": [
        19568,
        19674
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, you cannot perform a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Copy Blob<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dd894037.aspx)</ept> operation on that blob as long as the disk is attached to a VM.",
      "pos": [
        19675,
        19839
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Instead, first create a snapshot of that blob by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Snapshot Blob<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/ee691971.aspx)</ept> REST API method, and then perform the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Copy Blob<ept id=\"p2\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dd894037.aspx)</ept> of the snapshot to copy the attached disk.",
      "pos": [
        19840,
        20117
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Alternatively, you can detach the disk and then perform any necessary operations on the underlying blob.",
      "pos": [
        20118,
        20222
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Important Notes:",
      "pos": [
        20228,
        20244
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The number of snapshots for a single blob is limited to 100.",
      "pos": [
        20248,
        20308
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A snapshot can be taken every 10 minutes at most.",
      "pos": [
        20309,
        20358
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The maximum capacity for snapshots per Premium Storage account is 10 TB.",
      "pos": [
        20361,
        20433
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that snapshot capacity refers to the total amount of data in snapshots only, and does not include data in the base blob.",
      "pos": [
        20434,
        20559
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To maintain geo-redundant copies of your snapshots, you can copy snapshots from a premium storage account to a geo-redundant standard storage account by using AzCopy or Copy Blob.",
      "pos": [
        20562,
        20741
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How to use AzCopy with Microsoft Azure Storage<ept id=\"p1\">](storage-use-azcopy.md)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Copy Blob<ept id=\"p2\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dd894037.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        20742,
        20911
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        20914,
        21147
      ],
      "content": "For detailed information on performing REST operations against page blobs in Premium Storage accounts, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Using Blob Service Operations with Azure Premium Storage<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=521969)</ept> in the MSDN library."
    },
    {
      "content": "Using Linux VMs with Premium Storage",
      "pos": [
        21152,
        21188
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Please refer to important instructions below for configuring your Linux VMs on Premium Storage:",
      "pos": [
        21189,
        21284
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For all Premium Storage disks with cache setting as either “ReadOnly” or “None”, you must disable “barriers” while mounting the file system in order to achieve the scalability targets for Premium Storage.",
      "pos": [
        21288,
        21492
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You do not need barriers for this scenario because the writes to Premium Storage backed disks are durable for these cache settings.",
      "pos": [
        21493,
        21624
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the write request successfully completes, data has been written to the persistent store.",
      "pos": [
        21625,
        21718
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Please use the following methods for disabling “barriers” depending on your file system:",
      "pos": [
        21719,
        21807
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        21814,
        21938
      ],
      "content": "If you use <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>reiserFS<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, disable barriers using the mount option “barrier=none” (For enabling barriers, use “barrier=flush”)"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        21945,
        22063
      ],
      "content": "If you use <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ext3/ext4<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, disable barriers using the mount option “barrier=0” (For enabling barriers, use “barrier=1”)"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        22070,
        22191
      ],
      "content": "If you use <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>XFS<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, disable barriers using the mount option “nobarrier” (For enabling barriers, use the option “barrier”)"
    },
    {
      "content": "For Premium Storage disks with cache setting “ReadWrite”, barriers should be enabled for durability of writes.",
      "pos": [
        22195,
        22305
      ]
    },
    {
